❯ Explain the project structure to me                                           

  Thought for 1s, read 4 files (ctrl+o to expand)

● Project Overview

  The expense‑tracker repository is a small Flask‑based web application scaffold
  that is used as a learning project for building an expense‑tracking web app.
  The code is organized into a classic Flask project layout with clear
  separation between the back‑end (Python), the templating layer (HTML), and the
  static assets (CSS/JS).

  ---
  Directory / File Structure

  expense-tracker/
  │
  ├─ .git/                     # Git metadata (repository history, branches,
  etc.)
  ├─ database/
  │   ├─ __init__.py           # Makes `database` a package (can hold DB
  scripts)
  │   └─ db.py                 # ★ TODO: implement SQLite connection & table
  setup
  │
  ├─ static/
  │   ├─ css/
  │   │   └─ style.css         # Global stylesheet (variables, layout,
  components)
  │   └─ js/
  │       └─ main.js           # Placeholder for client‑side JavaScript
  │
  ├─ templates/
  │   ├─ base.html             # Master layout (navbar, footer, CSS/JS includes)
  │   ├─ landing.html          # Home page placeholder
  │   ├─ login.html            # Login page placeholder
  │   ├─ register.html         # Registration page placeholder
  │   └─ … (other partials)    # Individual page templates that extend
  `base.html`
  │
  ├─ app.py                    # Main Flask entry point (routes, app factory,
  config)
  ├─ requirements.txt          # Python dependencies (Flask, Werkzeug, pytest,
  …)
  └─ … (other project files)   # e.g., README, .gitignore, etc.

  Key Components Explained

  Component: Flask Application
  Location: app.py
  Purpose: Entry point that creates the Flask app, registers routes, and runs
  the
    server (app.run(debug=True, port=5001))
  What You’ll See / Implement: Routes defined for /, /login, /register,
    /expenses/* etc. All currently return placeholder strings (e.g., “Add
  expense
     — coming in Step 7”).
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  Component: Database Layer
  Location: database/db.py
  Purpose: Intended spot for SQLite connection (get_db()), schema creation
    (init_db()), and seed data (seed_db())
  What You’ll See / Implement: Right now it only contains comments describing
  the
    required functions; you will later add actual SQLAlchemy or sqlite3 code.
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  Component: Templates
  Location: templates/
  Purpose: Jinja2 HTML templates that Flask renders. base.html is the master
    layout; other pages (landing, login, register) extend it.
  What You’ll See / Implement: Includes a navigation bar, footer, and blocks for

    page‑specific content and extra scripts. The layout uses CSS variables
    defined in static/css/style.css.
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  Component: Static Assets
  Location: static/
  Purpose: Public‑facing CSS and JavaScript files served as‑is.
  What You’ll See / Implement: style.css defines Design Tokens (--ink, --accent,

    etc.) and styles for the navbar, hero sections, cards, buttons, etc. main.js

    is currently a stub comment—students add JavaScript as features are built.
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  Component: Root‑level Files
  Location: .gitignore, requirements.txt
  Purpose: Project metadata and Python dependencies.
  What You’ll See / Implement: requirements.txt lists Flask, Werkzeug, pytest,
    etc., so you can pip install them.
  ────────────────────────────────────────
  Component: Configuration / Scripts
  Location: (none yet)
  Purpose: Future steps may involve additional configuration files (e.g.,
    environment variables, Celery workers).
  What You’ll See / Implement: Not present yet; you may add them later.

  ---
  How the Pieces Fit Together

  1. Routing (app.py)
    - Flask maps URL paths to Python view functions.
    - Example: @app.route("/") renders landing.html.
    - All routes currently return simple placeholder text, but they will later
  render full HTML templates that use the base.html layout.
  2. Template Rendering
    - Jinja2 syntax ({{ url_for('static', filename='css/style.css') }}) injects
  static asset URLs into the HTML.
    - Child templates (login.html, register.html, etc.) extend base.html and
  only provide the content for the <main> block.
  3. Styling
    - static/css/style.css contains a full design system (color variables,
  spacing, button styles).
    - Because the CSS is scoped with CSS variables, you can easily them‑ify the
  whole UI later.
  4. Client‑Side Interactions
    - static/js/main.js is reserved for any JavaScript you’ll add (e.g., form
  validation, dynamic charts).
    - Right now it only contains a comment, signalling “students will add
  JavaScript here as features are built”.
  5. Database
    - In the next implementation step you’ll populate database/db.py with SQLite
  connection logic and create tables such as users, expenses, etc.
    - Flask’s teardown_appcontext can automatically close connections after each
  request.

  ---
  Quick Visual Walkthrough

  expense-tracker/
  ├─ app.py               # ← Flask routes and app factory
  ├─ requirements.txt     # ← pip dependencies
  ├─ database/
  │   └─ db.py            # ← (future) DB connection & schema
  ├─ static/
  │   ├─ css/style.css    # ← Global styling & design tokens
  │   └─ js/main.js       # ← Placeholder for JS
  └─ templates/
      ├─ base.html        # ← Master layout (nav, footer, blocks)
      ├─ landing.html     # ← Home page (extends base)
      ├─ login.html       # ← Login page (extends base)
      └─ register.html    # ← Register page (extends base)

  ---
  What to Do Next (if you’re continuing the curriculum)

  1. Database Setup – Implement the functions described in database/db.py and
  wire them into app.py.
  2. Replace Placeholder Text – Turn the “coming in Step X” messages into real,
  working pages that interact with the DB.
  3. Add JavaScript – Populate static/js/main.js with any client‑side validation
  or UI enhancements.
  4. Styling Tweaks – Adjust static/css/style.css variables/theme to match your
  visual design.

  Feel free to ask if you’d like a deeper dive into any specific part (e.g., the
  Jinja2 template inheritance, how url_for works, or how to structure the
  SQLite schema). Happy coding!
